== Reception ==
{{Double image|right|Pritzker pavilion looking north night logan reed.jpg|180|Pritzker pavilion east back far.jpg|180|While most critics have praised the pavilion (left, at night), others have criticized its exposed beams and angular shapes (right).||Night view of a bandshell framed by large curved metal surfaces and lit with orange-golden light. A trellis is visible overhead and very tall brightly lit skyscrapers are in the background.|View of the back of a building where many large metal struts support angular metal plates, braced with geometric grids. There are skyscrapers in the background.}}
Critics have said that Jay Pritzker Pavilion is the highlight of Millennium Park. ''[[Fodor's]]'' travel guide described it as the park's "showstopper" and "stunning", praising its stainless steel and sound system, as well as the variety of events it hosts.<ref name = "Fodors">{{cite web|url=http://www.fodors.com/world/north-america/usa/illinois/chicago/review-111571.html|title=Millennium Park|accessdate=2008-07-30|publisher=Fodor's Travel}} Note: This incorrectly lists the Jay Pritzker Pavilion as hosting the Chicago Blues and Chicago Jazz Festivals.</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called the pavilion "dynamic" and recommended it as one of two must-see attractions in the park,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,995369,00.html|title=Windy City Redux|accessdate=2008-07-30|date=2004-10-11|author=Roston, Eric|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> while one ''[[New York Times]]'' writer found herself standing "agog" at what appeared to her to be a "celestial gateway to another universe" and a frame for the sky.<ref name=NSaCWGaG>{{cite news|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F01EED7163AF936A25754C0A9629C8B63|title= Nature; Softening a City With Grit and Grass|accessdate=2008-07-30|date=2004-07-15|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Raver, Anne|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080617003432/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F01EED7163AF936A25754C0A9629C8B63 |archivedate = June 17, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> ''[[Lonely Planet]]'' travel guide called the pavilion the anchor of the park,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/worldguide/usa/chicago/sights/1000317530?list=true|title=Millennium Park|accessdate=2008-07-30|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications}}</ref> and the 2004 Year in Review issue of ''Time'' described it as the park's crown jewel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/bestandworst/2004/arch.html|title=Best & Worst 2004: The Best Architecture|author=Lacayo, Richard|accessdate=2008-07-31|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=2004-12-18|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080510154129/http://www.time.com/time/bestandworst/2004/arch.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=2008-05-10}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' described the bandshell as a landmark and the centerpiece of Millennium Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/664721801.html?dids=664721801:664721801&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+15%2C+2004&author=Debbie+Howlett&pub=USA+TODAY&edition=&startpage=A.03&desc=Donors%27+cash+turns+city+green+%3B+Private+contributions+make+Millennium+Park+a+reality+in+Chicago|title=Donors' cash turns city green ; Private contributions make Millennium Park a reality in Chicago|accessdate=2008-07-31|date=2004-07-15|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Howlett, Debbie}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/664722041.html?dids=664722041:664722041&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+15%2C+2004&author=Debbie+Howlett&pub=USA+TODAY&edition=&startpage=A.03&desc=%27A+band+shell+on+steroids%27|title=A band shell on steroids|accessdate=2008-07-31|date=2004-07-15|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Howlett, Debbie}}</ref> Another critic described the pavilion as the "most spectacular structure to go up in early-twenty-first-century Chicago".<ref name=PaL/>

According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', the bandshell's acoustics are unparalleled compared to any contemporary outdoor venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/63ad44b2-2196-11da-a603-00000e2511c8.html|title=Classical city soars above Capone clich<U+00E9>s|accessdate=2008-07-31|date=2005-09-10|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|work=[[The Financial Times]]|author=Daniel, Caroline and Jeremy Grant}}</ref> Critics say that musicians have lauded the onstage acoustics.<ref name=PaL/> Another ''Financial Times'' critic noted that Gehry revisited some of his past design [[Motif (visual arts)|motifs]], such as his use of stainless steel, and explored new ones such as the trellis and sound system.<ref>{{cite news | <!-- url=http://search.ft.com/ftArticle?queryText=%22Cloud%20Gate%22%20Chicago&y=0&aje=true&x=0&id=040720000796&ct=0 -->|title=How a steel bean gave Chicago fresh pride|accessdate=2008-07-31|date=2004-07-20|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|work=[[The Financial Times]]|author=Daniel, Caroline}}</ref> This sentiment was echoed by others.<ref name=PaL>Pridmore and Larson, pp. 272<U+2013>3</ref>  However, von Rhein noted that the sound is not of uniform quality throughout the venue and opined that the optimal sonics are toward the back of the seated area and front of the lawn.<ref name="von Rhein"/>
[[File:Pritzker Pavilion band shell Millennium Park Chicago.JPG|thumb|left|From Michigan Avenue]]
Despite the praise it has received, the pavilion has its blemishes: the supporting north side of the structure along Randolph Street has attracted criticism for not being pleasing to the eye, and some observers found the exposed supporting proscenium braces offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lynnbecker.com/repeat/Gehry/gehrybaroque.htm|accessdate=2007-09-21|title=Frank Gehry, Millennium Park and the development of the Techno-Baroque|author=Becker, Lynn|publisher=Lynn Becker |work=Repeat}}</ref> Critic Fred Bernstein of ''The New York Times'' felt that the smooth rounded trellis and sharp-edged bandshell were geometrically discordant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9901E2D61F3BF93BA25754C0A9629C8B63|title= Art/Architecture; Big Shoulders, Big Donors, Big Art|accessdate=2008-06-01|date=2004-07-18|author=Bernstein, Fred A.|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> A review in the ''Chicago Tribune'' criticized the "ugly concrete structure" surrounding the [[mixing console]] in the midst of the fixed seats as the pavilion's "biggest design miscalculation", and called for it be moved.<ref name="von Rhein"/> Although modern practice is to locate the sound console in with the audience,<ref>{{cite book | title = Illustrated theatre production guide | first= John | last = Holloway | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=UkFh8t5SsNQC&pg=PA8#v=onepage&q=&f=false | page = 8 | year = 2002 | isbn = 0-240-80493-7 | publisher = Focal Press, Elsevier Science | location = Burlington, Massachusetts | accessdate = 2010-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title = Theatre sound | first = John A. | last = Leonard | page = 16 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=6KTPirqYw5wC&pg=PA16&dq=operating+position+auditorium#v=onepage&q=operating%20position%20auditorium&f=false | year = 2001 | isbn = 0-87830-116-X | publisher = Theatre Arts Books/Routledge | location = New York, New York | accessdate = 2010-01-13}}</ref> Gehry said at a symposium after the park's opening that he wanted "to scrap the big box of a sound booth that sprang up like a weed in the center of the pavilion's seating".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/the-six-million-dollar-birdcage-quade-v-donovan-continued/Content?oid=916201 | title = The Six Million Dollar Birdcage: The Pritzker Pavilion may be pretty, but it can't replace the Petrillo Music Shell | author = Isaacs, Deanna | work = [[Chicago Reader]] | date = 2004-07-29 | accessdate = 2010-01-13 }}</ref>
The director of Millennium Park was honored for his contribution to creating "one of the most accessible parks&nbsp;<U+2013> not just in the United States but possibly the world" in a 2005 [[accessibility]] award ceremony held at the pavilion.<ref name=PVA>{{cite web|url=http://pva.convio.net/site/DocServer/PN_BFA_2005_Article.pdf?docID=1921|title=Chicago's New Class Act|accessdate=2007-12-21|year=2005|month=July|publisher=Paralyzed Veterans of America|format=PDF|work=PN|author=Deyer, Joshua}}</ref> The pavilion's stage is reached by gently sloped ramps instead of stairs, as part of the park's overall accessibility design.<ref name=PVA/> The decision to save money and not slope the Great Lawn as much as originally planned was not universally popular.<ref name = "flounders">{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EDB47DD36D61F4A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=AA98CDC331574F0ABEAFF732B33DC0B2|title=Millennium Park flounders as deadlines, budget blown&nbsp;<U+2013> Poor plans, constant changes slow progress, drive up price&nbsp;<U+2013> and city taxpayers may have to help make up difference|accessdate=2008-07-28|date=2001-08-05|publisher=NewsBank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Martin, Andrew and Laurie Cohen}}</ref> However, Gehry said that the actual slope of the lawn was more accommodating to people with disabilities and better able to accommodate activities than the original plan.<ref>Gilfoyle, p. 168.</ref>
{{Clear}}

{{Panorama
|image = File:Pano-chicago.jpg
|alt = Futuristic view of a green lawn with people scattered on it, beneath a metal trellis supported on shiny metal pillars. The trellis leads to a bandshell surrounded by curved plates of shiny metal, with many tall skyscrapers in the background.
|caption = Panoramic view of the Great Lawn, trellis, and bandshell at Jay Pritzker Pavilion in May 2009. Among the buildings pictured in the background are (left to right) [[The Heritage at Millennium Park|The Heritage]], [[Smurfit-Stone Building]], [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (Chicago)|Trump International Hotel and Tower]], [[One Prudential Plaza]], [[Two Prudential Plaza]], [[Aon Center (Chicago)|Aon Center]], [[Aqua (skyscraper)|Aqua]], [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Tower]], [[340 on the Park]], [[The Buckingham (Chicago, Illinois)|The Buckingham]], [[400 East Randolph]], and [[Harbor Point (skyscraper)|Harbor Point]].
